Import STAR data

read_measurement_names <- 
  tibble(orig_col_name = c("Number of input reads", 
                           "Uniquely mapped reads number",
                           "Number of reads mapped to multiple loci"),
         short_name = c("Total_reads", "UM_reads", "Multimapped"))

parse_star_log <- function(file_name) {
  #file_name="../../scratch/00245bb9-b207-4648-b26e-bf16ec38103a.Log.final.out"
  tibble(raw=scan(file_name, what = "list", sep ="\n",  quiet = TRUE)) %>%
    filter(grepl(paste(read_measurement_names$orig_col_name,collapse="|"), raw)) %>%
    # when unnest_wider is NOT available
    mutate(measurement_name = gsub(" \\|\t.*$", "", raw),
           measurement_value = as.numeric(gsub("^.*\t", "", raw)),
           star_results_file = gsub(paste0(scratch_dir, "/"), "", file_name),
           measurement_name = str_trim(measurement_name)) %>%
    select(-raw)

Calculate percentages for reference range calcs

read_counts_with_ref_range_fractions <- selected_read_counts %>% 
  arrange(desc(Total_reads)) %>% 
  mutate(pct_unmapped_of_total = (Total_reads - Mapped)/Total_reads,
         pct_multi_mapped_of_mapped = Multimapped/Mapped, # Mapped = UM + MM
         pct_dupe_of_mapped = (Mapped - MND) / Mapped,
         pct_non_exonic_of_non_dupe = (MND - MEND)/MND)

read_fracs_with_ref_range_fractions_long <- read_counts_with_ref_range_fractions %>%
  select(c(sample_id, starts_with("pct_"))) %>% 
#  pivot_longer(cols=-sample_id, names_to="ref_range_name") 
    gather(key="ref_range_name", value = "value", -sample_id)

Calculate reference ranges

ref_range_codes <- as_tibble(list(ref_range_abbrev = c("NM", "MM", "D", "NE"), ref_range_description = c("Not mapped", 
"Multi-mapped", "Duplicate reads", "Non exonic reads"), ref_range_name = c("pct_unmapped_of_total", 
"pct_multi_mapped_of_mapped", "pct_dupe_of_mapped", "pct_non_exonic_of_non_dupe"
)))

ref_range_stats <- function(mean1, sd1) {
  c(mean_minus_one_sd = mean1-sd1,
    mean_plus_one_sd = mean1+sd1,
    mean_minus_two_sd = mean1-(2*sd1),
    mean_plus_two_sd = mean1+(2*sd1))}

ref_range_mean_sd <- read_counts_with_ref_range_fractions %>%
  select(starts_with("pct_")) %>% 
  gather(key="ref_range_name") %>%
  # pivot_longer(cols=everything(), names_to="ref_range_name") %>%
  group_by(ref_range_name) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(value), sd = sd(value)) %>%
  mutate(stats = pmap(list(mean, sd), ref_range_stats))  %>%
  # unnest_wider(stats)
  mutate(r = map(stats, ~ data.frame(t(.)))) %>%
  unnest(r) %>%
  select(-stats)

all_stats <- ref_range_mean_sd %>% 
  select(-sd) %>%
  gather(key="stat_name", value = "value", -ref_range_name) %>%
#  pivot_longer(cols = c(-ref_range_name), names_to="stat_name") %>%
  mutate(minmax = ifelse(grepl("plus", stat_name), "max",
                         ifelse(grepl("minus", stat_name), "min",
                                "mean")),
         stat = gsub("^.*_([[:lower:]]{3}_.*)", "\\1", stat_name),
        ref_range_name = factor(ref_range_name, 
                                levels = ref_range_codes$ref_range_name))

Groom reference ranges

read_type_pct_thresholds <- all_stats %>% 
  filter(stat == "two_sd") %>%
  select(-stat, -stat_name) %>%
  spread(key = "minmax", value = "value") %>%
#  pivot_wider(names_from = minmax, 
#              values_from = value) %>%
  rename(min_pct = min, max_pct = max)

Identify samples within reference range

read_fracs_with_thresholds <- left_join(read_fracs_with_ref_range_fractions_long, read_type_pct_thresholds, by = "ref_range_name") %>%
  rename(sample_value = value) %>%
  mutate(within_limits = ifelse(sample_value > min_pct,
                                ifelse(sample_value<max_pct,
                                       "within_limits",
                                       "above_limit"),
                                "below_limit"))
## Warning: Column `ref_range_name` joining character vector and factor,
## coercing into character vector
n_ref_ranges <- n_distinct(read_type_pct_thresholds$ref_range_name)

samples_within_limits <- read_fracs_with_thresholds %>% 
  group_by(sample_id) %>%
  filter(sum(grepl("within_limits", within_limits)) == n_ref_ranges) %>%
  pull(sample_id) %>% unique

depth_status <- read_counts_with_ref_range_fractions %>%
  select(sample_id, MEND) %>%
  mutate(
    status=ifelse( MEND<10E6,
                   "<10M_MEND_reads",
                   ifelse(MEND<20E6, 
                          "10-20 MEND_reads",
                          ">20M_MEND_reads")
    ),
  all_read_types_within_read_type_limits = sample_id %in% samples_within_limits,
  within_read_type_limits_label = c( "not_WNL", "WNL")[1 + all_read_types_within_read_type_limits]
  )

# How many samples were outside ref range?
table(read_fracs_with_thresholds$within_limits)

##   above_limit   below_limit within_limits 
##           162             5          3713
# How many samples in each MEND depth group were outside ref range?
tabyl(depth_status, within_read_type_limits_label, status)
##  within_read_type_limits_label <10M_MEND_reads >20M_MEND_reads
##                        not_WNL               8              86
##                            WNL               0             849
##  10-20 MEND_reads
##                18
##                 9
threshold_flag_annotations <- read_fracs_with_thresholds %>% 
  left_join(ref_range_codes, by="ref_range_name") %>%
  mutate(threshold_code = ifelse(within_limits == "within_limits", NA, ref_range_abbrev)) %>%
  group_by(sample_id) %>%
  summarize(flagged_thresholds = paste(na.omit(threshold_code), collapse=", "))

read_fracs_with_thresholds <- read_fracs_with_thresholds %>% 
  left_join(threshold_flag_annotations, by="sample_id")

Visualize overlap in flags accrued per sample

stat_names_plus_MEND <- c(stat_names, "MEND count")
stat_label_plus_MEND  <- c(stat_label, "MEND count range")


flag_analysis <- read_fracs_with_thresholds_anno %>%
  bind_rows(depth_status %>%
              mutate(ref_range_name = "MEND count") %>%
              rename(within_limits=status)) %>%
  filter(! sample_id %in% samples_within_limits) %>%
  group_by(sample_id) %>%
  mutate(n_flags=sum(within_limits == "within_limits")) %>%
  arrange(desc(n_flags)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(sample_id = factor(sample_id, levels = unique(sample_id)),
         ref_range_name = factor(ref_range_name, levels = rev(stat_names_plus_MEND)) )
## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): binding factor and character vector,
## coercing into character vector
## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): binding character and factor vector,
## coercing into character vector
## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): binding factor and character vector,
## coercing into character vector
## Warning in bind_rows_(x, .id): binding character and factor vector,
## coercing into character vector
ggplot(flag_analysis) + 
  geom_tile(aes(x=sample_id, y=ref_range_name, fill = within_limits)) +
#  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
   theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks.x = element_blank()) +
  scale_y_discrete(breaks=stat_names_plus_MEND, labels=stat_label_plus_MEND) +
  scale_fill_manual("", values=limit_and_MEND_vec) +
  ylab("") + xlab("Sample")

Samples are ordered by the number of read fractions for which they exceed the reference range. Samples that exceed the range of non-exonic reads often only exceed that range and no other. Conversely, samples that exceed the unmapped threshold often also exceed the multi-mapper threshold; some of those samples also exceed the duplicate read threshold.

  plot_layout(widths = c(1, 6)) + 
  plot_annotation(
  title = "Breakdown of read counts by reference range status",
  subtitle = "Samples outside of reference ranges do not systemically differ in total
  read counts, but they do have fewer total MEND reads",
  caption = stringr::str_wrap('A. Total reads in all samples. B. Total reads in samples by reference range status for each of the four reference ranges. C. Total MEND reads in all samples. D. Total MEND reads in samples by reference range status for each of the four reference ranges', width = 120),
  tag_levels = 'A'
)

As seen in C and D, and by definition, samples that have high fractions of non-MEND reads have fewer MEND reads than other samples. However, they do not vary much from other samples in the number of total reads (A and B). In other words, the number of total reads does not determine whether a sample is within range for a subcomponent of the sample.

p_gene_counts_in_all <- ggplot(read_fracs_with_thresholds_anno2 %>% 
         select(sample_id, genes_gt_zero) %>%
         distinct %>%
           mutate(value_name="all samples"), 
         aes(y=genes_gt_zero/1e3, x=value_name)
         ) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  EnvStats::stat_n_text(size=3) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank()) +
  ylab("Number of genes (thousands)") 


p_gene_counts_by_ref_range <- ggplot(read_fracs_with_thresholds_anno2, aes(x=within_limits, y=genes_gt_zero/1e3)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  EnvStats::stat_n_text(size = 3) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c("within_limits", "below_limit", "above_limit"),
                   labels = c("within", "below", "above")) +
  facet_wrap(~ref_range_name, nrow=1, labeller = labeller(
    ref_range_name=stat_label) ) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank())

  plot_layout(widths = c(1, 6)) + 
  plot_annotation(
  title = "Breakdown of measured genes by reference range status",
  caption = stringr::str_wrap('A. Genes measured in all samples. B. Genes measured in samples by reference range status for each of the four reference ranges.', width = 80),
  tag_levels = 'A'
)

Samples that exceed unmapped, multi-mapped or duplicate read fraction thresholds generally measure fewer genes than their within-range counterparts. The reverse is true for samples that exceed the non-exonic read fraction threshold. If it reflects genomic contamination, that genomic contamination might also result in apparent exonic reads from DNA from genes that are not producing RNA in the same. In that scenario, the non-exonic reads would not be directly contributing to the higher gene count.
